Fixed.
The problem appeared when trying to call on 'this' a method defined in an
interface from an abstract class, if there is not concrete implementation of the
method in the supertype hierarchy of the abstract class.

A test case :

public class Bug_44591 {

  interface inter {
    void foo();
  }

  abstract class abs implements inter {
    void bar() {
      foo();   // <--- breakpoint here
    }
  }

  class concrete extends abs {
    public void foo() {
      System.out.println("test");
    }
  }

  public static void main(String[] args) {
    new Bug_44591().new concrete().bar();
  }
}

when the breakpoint is hit, try to evaluate 'foo()'.

The implementation was no managing the fact that it's possible to call a method
from a class, where there is no concrete implementation of the method in the
supertype hierarchy.

Changes in ASTInstructionCompiler.
